'''Cleofé Elsa Calderón''' (October 26, 1929 &ndash; March 19, 2007) was an Argentine botanist.

In 1976, Calderón rediscovered ''[[Anomochloa]]'' in [[Bahia]], Brazil, with the help of assistant Talmon Soares dos Santos. By identifying this tropical forest grass, Calderón provided specimens for detailed morphological and anatomical study that confirmed it as a grass.<ref name="CaldéronObituary">{{cite journal|last=Calderón|first=Cleofé|title=Cleofé E. Calderón (1929-2007)|journal=Bamboo Science and Culture|year=2008|volume=21|issue=1|pages=1–8|url=http://www.bamboo.org/publications/e107_files/downloads/ABSJournal-vol21.pdf|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref>

In October 1971, Calderón performed field operations and collected living materials of a new genus of grasses; the genus was named after her: ''[[Calderonella]]''.<ref name=CalderonellaGenus>{{cite journal|last=Soderstrom|first=Thomas R.|author2=Henry F. Decker|title=Calderonella, A New Genus of Grasses, and its Relationships to the Centostecoid Genera|journal=Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden|year=1973|volume=60|issue=2|pages=427–441|jstor=2395091|doi=10.2307/2395091}}</ref>

