{{nihongo|'''Kiyoo Wadati'''|和達 清夫|Wadachi Kiyoo|extra=September 8, 1902 – January 5, 1995}} was an early [[seismologist]] at the Central Meteorological Observatory of [[Japan]] (now known as the [[Japan Meteorological Agency]]), researching deep ([[subduction zone]]) earthquakes.  His name is attached to the [[Wadati–Benioff zone]]. It was Wadati's 1928 paper on shallow and deep earthquakes, comparing maximum below surface displacement against distance from the [[epicentre]], which led [[Charles Richter]] to develop his [[Richter magnitude scale|earthquake magnitude scale]] in 1935.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Wadati, Kiyoo |first=Yasumoto |last=Suzuki |encyclopedia=Complete Dictionary of Scientific Biography |volume=25 |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |location=Detroit |year=2008 |pages=199&ndash;201 |url=http://go.galegroup.com.prox.lib.ncsu.edu/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CCX2830906185&v=2.1&u=nclivensu&it=r&p=GVRL&sw=w |accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref>

