{{Quasar | name = [[LBQS]] 1429-008 | image = | epoch = [[J2000]] | ra = {{RA|14|32|29.25}} | dec = {{DEC|-01|06|16.1}} | constellation name = [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]] | z = 2.08<ref name=SIMBAD>[http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-id?protocol=html&Ident=QSO+1429-008&NbIdent=1&Radius=2&Radius.unit=arcmin&submit=submit+id Simbad]</ref> | type = QSO | dist_ly = 10.5 [[light-year|gly]] | appmag_v = 17.7 | size_v = | notes = | names = [[LBQS]] 1429-0053, [[Quasar|QSO]] B1429-0053, [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey|SDSS]] J143229.24-010616.0, [[VV2006]] J143229.2-010617, [[FIRST]] J143229.3-010614, [[Quasar|QSO]] B1429-008A, [[HB93]] 1429-008, [[Quasar|QSO]] B1429-0053A, [[Quasar|QSO]] J1432-0106A, [[Quasar|QSO]] B1429-008 }}
'''LBQS 1429-008''' ('''QQ 1429−008''', '''QQ 1432−0106''', '''QQQ J1432−0106''') is a physical triple [[quasar]].<ref>Sky & Telescope [http://www.skyandtelescope.com/news/5141272.html The First Triple Quasar] January 10, 2007</ref> It was the first physical triple discovered.
